AGI - Israel's war in Gaza, which has been going on for more than seven months since the attack on Hamas against Israel on 7 October, has relaunched the global thrust for the recognition of a Palestinian state. Norway, Spain and Ireland > announced on Wednesday the intention of recognizing a State of Palestine, breaking with the long-standing position supported by the Western powers, according to which a Palestinian State can only be born in the context of a peace negotiated with Israel. According to the Palestinian Authority, which has limited powers in some parts of the occupied West Bank, 143 of the 193 member countries of the United Nations already recognize a State of Palestine. Among these are many Middle Eastern, African and Asian countries, but not the United States, Canada, most Western Europe, Australia, Japan and South Korea. In April, the United States used their veto to the UN Security Council to prevent the Palestinian request from becoming a full member of the United Nations.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
Here is a brief summary of the search for a state by the Palestinians:
&nbsp;
<
<li>1988: ARAFAT PROCLAMA LO STATO.> On 15 November 1988, during the first Palestinian intifada, the Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat > proclaimed an independent Palestinian state with Jerusalem as a capital. He announced in Algiers, at a meeting of the Palestinian National Council in exile, that he adopted the solution of the two States as an objective, with Israeli and Palestinian States independent of each other. Algeria has become the first country to officially recognize an independent Palestinian state. Within a few weeks, dozens of other countries, including most of the Arab world, India, Turkey, most of Africa and several countries in Central and Eastern Europe, followed the example. The next wave of awards took place between the end of 2010 and the beginning of 2011, at a time of crisis of the peace process in the Middle East. A series of South American countries, including Argentina, Brazil and Chile, responded to the Palestinian appeal to support their state claims. This happened in response to Israel's decision to end the temporary ban on building Jewish settlements in the occupied West Bank.
</ul
&nbsp;
<
<li>2011-2012: RECOGNITION BY UNITED NATIONS.> In 2011, with peace talks in stall, the Palestinians decided to carry out a campaign for full membership of the UN of the State of Palestine. The campaign failed, but on 31 October of the same year, with an innovative move, the United Nations Cultural Agency, UNESCO, voted to accept Palestinians as full members. The decision triggered a furious reaction from Israel and the United States, which suspended their funding from the body based in Paris. In 2018 they abandoned the <a href="https://www.agi.it/tag/unesco/"> UNESCO</a>, although the United States returned last year. In November 2012, the Palestinian flag was first placed at the United Nations in New York, after the General Assembly voted by a large majority to update the status of Palestinians to "No Member State observer". Three years later, the International Criminal Court also accepted Palestine as a Member State.
</ul
&nbsp;
<
<li> 2014: WARNING FIRST IN THE OCCIDENTAL EUROPE.> In 2014, Sweden, which has a large Palestinian community, became the first EU member in Western Europe to recognize a Palestinian state. The move followed months of almost daily confrontations in East Jerusalem, surrounded by Israel. A Palestinian state had previously been recognized by six other European countries: Bulgaria, Cyprus, Czech Republic, Hungary, Poland and Romania. Israel reacted with anger to the Stockholm move, with the then Foreign Minister Avigdor Lieberman > who told the Swedes that "the relations in the Middle East are much more complex than IKEA's self-assembled furniture." < >
</ul
&nbsp;
<
<li>2024: NEW SPINTA IN EUROPE.>&nbsp; Israel's relentless offensive in Gaza, which has caused at least 35.647 deaths, according to the Ministry of Health of the territory, as a reprisal for the killing of more than 1,170 people in Israel by Hamas, has raised support in Europe for the creation of a Palestinian State. Norway, Spain and Ireland have declared that they will recognize a Palestinian state by 28 May, challenging the threats of Israel, which recalled its envoys from Ireland and Norway to discuss the move. Malta and Slovenia, in March, also called themselves "ready to recognize Palestine" when "the circumstances will be right". Australia has also recently ventilated the possibility to unilaterally support the &nbsp;Palestinian statues. President Emmanuel Macron also stated that the question of recognition of a Palestinian State without negotiated peace is no longer a tabooo for France. &nbsp;</li>
</ul
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
