AGI - Thousands of Israelis are protesting in Tel Aviv and Jerusalem, calling for immediate release of hostages a few hours after the broadcast of the footage showing the abduction of five Israeli soldier women by terrorists led by Hamas on October 7. The video shows the soldiers, some with the bloody face, to the mercy of armed militiamen.&nbsp; Tel Aviv protest is taking place outside the IDF military headquarters in Kirya, while the war cabinet convened a hostage meeting. The protesters lit a bonfire in the street, blocking traffic in both directions. The protest in Jerusalem is taking place in front of the office of Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu in Jerusalem, advancing the same demands.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<em> The following video contains images that might affect the viewer and are not recommended for those who are particularly sensitive </em>
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
The decision to post the document was taken by military families, Liri Albag, Karina Ariev, Agam Berger, Daniela Gilboa and Naama Levy.&nbsp; The film was previously released by Hamas, according to the Host Families Forum. The campaign promoter group got it from the IDF, which had previously modified the video to exclude the most disturbing scenes. "Every new testimony about what happened to the hostages echoes the same tragic truth: we must bring them all home now," said the Home Families Forum in a press release. Women were kidnapped during a Hamas raid at the Israeli military base of Nahal Oz, near the north of the Gaza Strip.

