AGI - The United Kingdom will go to early elections in July > British Prime Minister Rishi Sunak decided to break the Hindus and start the procedures for the dissolution of the House of Commons and the elections will be held on 4 July > six months before the natural expiry of the legislature. The news, anticipated by the British media in the afternoon while a council of ad hoc ministers was underway, was official a few hours later by Sunak himself. The hypothesis of a surprise decision of the Prime Minister had begun to circulate already in the morning, when the group leader of the Scottish Independents, Stephen Flynn, during the Wednesday question time at the House of Commons had asked provocatively to the Premier if he was afraid to announce the date of the vote. Sunak had not responded explicitly, but he had just remembered that he "repetutely said that the elections will be held in the second half" of 2024. A few hours after the noise was confirmed by the Prime Minister.
&nbsp;
The Tory party led by Sunak remains largely behind the polls > compared to the Labour Opposition of Keir Starmer:> the last YouGov survey for the Times conducted last week, shows that the Conservatives are back by 27 points > compared to Labour. And within the party an iron arm has already opened: According to several British media a group of 'rebels' Tories against the early vote would already be collecting signatures to request the resignation of the Prime Minister. The reasons that led Sunak to decide for acceleration, according to observers, is mainly given by two elements. The first is the economy >: Sunak would use the recent positive data on the economy to try to limit the drop in consensus for his party, in a long time crisis.
&nbsp;
Moreover, with a higher debt than expected who will win the elections will have to increase taxes or cut public spending >. An option Sunak doesn't want to head. The second reason is related to the management of illegal immigration. The Rwandan Plan, or the forced transfer of illegal migrants to Africa, was a battle horse of the Conservative government, but also the most risky one both politically and legally: in case of failure of the plan, the decrease of consents of the Tories in autumn would be even more clearly.
&nbsp;
The Conservatives, writes the Times, enter the election campaign with a huge financial advantage (in the current year they collected donations of 35 million pounds, compared to those declared by Labour of 24 million pounds) but with a sharp disadvantage in terms of consensus that could bring back the Labour to power after 14 years.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
